\textbf{Sketching Antiderivatives}

Consider the sketch $\displaystyle f(x)$ below.

Provide a sketch of the antiderivative
$\displaystyle A(x) = \int_{a}^{x}f(s)\,ds$ for
$\displaystyle -1.5 < x < 1.5$. Make sure to clearly indicate local
maxima and minima of $\displaystyle A(x)$

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{M103W2013Q9Question.jpg}
\caption{M103W2013Q9Question.jpg}
\end{figure}

sols:
Attached is a picture. Notice that there is a local minimum at
$\displaystyle x = -0.4$ and a local maximum at
$\displaystyle x = -1.4$. Also note that plugging in \emph{a} into the
integral gives

$\displaystyle A(a) = \int_{a}^{a}f(s)\,ds = 0$.

